script: As seen in Table_, the repeated measures ANOVA shows that there is no significant difference between when the word and colour matched and when they did not match, with a P value of 0.661, which is not p < 0.05. Next, the trial effect showed a near significant P value of 0.056, indicating that participants speeds changed across Trials 1, 2, and 3, likely increasing as they got used to the software. Finally, the interaction between colour matching and trial showed a P value of 0.758, suggesting that the Stroop Effect remained insignificant throughout the trials. This may be due to the observed outliers, as shown in table_, with reaction times of 13 seconds for participant 3, and 19 seconds for participant 10. These abnormally large reaction times relative to the rest inflate the "Mean Square Residual" (1.023), or, in other words, the background noise, preventing us from seeing the actual effect. Moreover, in terms of accuracy, trial three had an accuracy of 90%, indicating that participants were very cautious. Some technical factors to note are that our sample size was 16 students, which is small, and that, since we used a digital format, we must consider that the time it takes to find a key on a keyboard is often much longer than the millisecond-level Stroop interference. Therefore, in conclusion, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, meaning the Stroop effect was not observed.
The repeated measures ANOVA showed no significant Stroop effect (p = 0.661) or interaction (p = 0.758). While speeds improved across trials (p = 0.056), outliers of 13s and 19s inflated the Mean Square Residual (1.023), masking the actual effect. High accuracy (90%) and keyboard latency further confounded results. Due to these factors and a small sample (N = 16), we fail to reject the null hypothesis.
